,Recommended,227100,10260410,"Posted: 27 May, 2014",all,Wizard of Jazz,"An excellent game. Granted, this is the first SE game I've played, but I thought that this game was fantastic, and was a lot of fun. To me, SE:NZA is structured similar to the Left 4 Dead series, with long campaign ""missions"" with safe house checkpoints inbetween.However, this game stands proudly as a unique and fun experience. I personally had a lot of fun while playing SE:NZA, and regardless of whether players want to be marksmen and take high-distance, high-risk shots, or instead run into hordes guns blazing with submachine guns and grenades, there is something for everyone. The game is fine in single player, but is best in multiplayer.Another HUGE bonus: this is one of the few zombie games (yes, UNIQUE Nazi Zombies!) that has OCCULT-based zombies. It's been a while since I've seen non-infected, non-chemically-alterted zombies. The Occult themes allow for NZA to be a fun, yet creepy experience that's good to play with friends.Some downsides however:- The game has a tendency to play at Low Priority. I don't understand why this is, but those with high-end computers might find the game chugging more than usual. It resets as soon as you start playing again. I still don't know how to fix this.- Enemies can get stuck on stairwells, and very rarely enemies will not spawn, forcing you to restart the level.- There are many achievements requiring one to play co-op. While I'm not opposed to co-op achievements, getting 2000 kills in co-op is useless, as you can simply set up a private, 1-player co-op lobby and get the achievement there.All and all, a good experience. Recommended."
