,Recommended,227100,4726862,"Posted: 19 March, 2013",all,Skullkan6,"Look, you may have heard bad things about this game zbut frankly, this is a game i'd call not that bad. Like with Dead Island, how you view it depends on how much you like zombies. As a game for those who enjoy zombies in survival horror, it's an 75-85/100, for everyone else lower that score about 15-25 points (and 60 is average). First of all it's a linear campaign designed for Co-op that's also playable in Singleplayer if you like choosing the lesser way to play the game. (This is NOT as the case was with Dead Island where both were enjoyable and challenging, the game is legitimately made for Co-op and not much more.) There is yet to be a survival mode nor has one been promised but don't let that disuade you, as the campaign offered is much better than you may expect.Now if I have to say this game's greatest strength out-loud other than the kill-cam, it's how it handles hordes and this game is somehow able to handle hordes of slow zombies better than any game i've ever seen, and yes that includes Left 4 Dead where zombies were basically lightly wet sponges in comparison. This is admittedly something that has to be seen in action or played, and at that in co-op as singleplayer scales the zombie count down considerably. I myself haven't run into too many bugs nor any game crippling ones other than the innability to adjust player voice chat volume in the options menu. I can't put it any better than this: If you are find paying $20 for an Okay game and love zombies to death (and hopefully have friends who feel the same) this probably a pretty good purchase for you. It's legitimately tense during many moments and as I said before handles hordes better than any zombie game i've ever seen. And just to set the record straight, they did actually appear to put a bit of effort into this."
