,Recommended,227100,13952943,"Posted: 11 January, 2015",all,Ikrani,"Kiss realism goodbye, because this game does not give two sheits about plausibility.While the campaign may only have a few levels, each one of those levels is a good length with a variety of ways to maim, maul and murderize the opposing undead, ranging from blowing them up with dynamite to making their heads explode with your side arm. Ammo is harder to find for some weapons, so constantly relying on your submachine gun and sidearm can sometimes get you into a tight spot.Headshots are really the only way to ensure the undead stay dead, lest they comeback to life. There are certain areas where what appear to be already-dead bodies turn out to be not-quite-dead-yet bodies, adding to the level of tension as you have to go around seeking sleeping corpses to put down while conserving your precious ammo. Those zombies you do kill disintegrate after a while, meaning you have to divide your time between fighting and looting ammo before it vanishes.The enemies in this game aren't particularly varied, what with two basic grunts, one fast-moving suicide bomber, one heavy weapons zombie (which can be real pain in the♥♥♥♥♥to kill by yourself), one undead sniper variant who can leap tall buildings in a single bound, and one boss. However, the game makes up for this by keeping the spaces tight and only allowing you breathing room when there's about fifty or so enemies trying to kill you.The Slow-Mo camera is there, and while it does keep the game interesting it can get a little annoying after a while when every kill you make is gratuitously showcased for your carnal boredom.The only complaints I have are the lack of scenery variety, the lack of enemy variety, and the fact that the characters don't really have much character to grow attached to like their Call of Duty counterparts. These are issues I hope were addressed in this game's sequel. Despite this, Sniper Elite: Nazi Zombie Army is still really enjoyable, easily replayable escapist fun."
